Email 1:

**2\. Inviting feedback is an invaluable tool as it helps you learn about yourself and come to terms with personal issues in ways you can’t on your own.**

There are two types of driven leaders. 

There is the stereotypical driven CEO. The high energy choleric who doesn’t have time for dumb answers or lousy employees. He’s in control and if you put up a fight, you’re out.

This is the control freak and it’s a stereotype: true in some cases, but not across the board.

Thankfully, there is an alternative to being a control freak and it’s only one simple mentality shift away. 

Control freaks result from insecure ambition. 

Control freaks are ambitious people who see only one route to achieving a goal. Therefore, any “rerouting” that an employee or partner attempts to make is a threat to a highly-cherished goal.

Control freaks see only one path--their path--and because they’re driven, they won’t let anyone deter them (or their companies) from that path.

The only way to dodge a life as a control freak is to ***become a lifelong Learner.***

Here are the three traits of Lifelong Learners:

1. Lifelong Learners are transparent: they disclose information about themselves  
2. Lifelong Learners invite feedback: they ask others to critique them and their work  
3. Lifelong Learners embrace healthy change: they make adjustments according to what they discover through intentional critique

No matter how valuable your end-goal may be and no matter how efficient you’ve made your strategy (or path) to get there--you can only gain hearing criticism and learning from it.

If you are free to admit areas where you’re growing or need to grow and invite feedback from those closest to you--and learn from it--your momentum will be unstoppable.

Email 2:  
**1\. You build trust by sharing personal information/struggles/joys/ambitions with people**

Trust is the foundation of any relationship. Every other aspect of a business, organization, or movement is built upon trust. Before customer’s purchase, they trust. Churches split when they stop trusting each other. Movements explode and companies disband when their leaders break trust. If trust is removed from a marriage, it begins to crumble. The only stops way to rebuild a marriage--or any relationship--is to rebuild trust. 

Like the leaning Tower of Pisa, relationships tilt and eventually fall unless grounded in trust.

So if trust is so essential to successful relationships, how do you build it?

Building a firm foundation of trust requires many materials. But one in particular stands out as the frame that binds it all together.

Above any other ingredient required to build trust, transparency is the most important.

Transparency comes in layers. Not everyone deserves to hear everything about your life. However, readily admitting struggles in both business and personal lives can build trust.

To get there, we start with by looking at the Johari Windows.

**The Johari Windows ![][image1]![][image2]**

The Johari Windows is a visual designed to help people better understand themselves and their relationships to others.

Originated by two psychologists in 1955, the windows are four quadrants of a plane created by two intersecting axes.

It is a visual designed to measure what you know about yourself, what others know about you, and what are blind-spots.

The x-axis is labeled “Ask” and the y-axis is labeled “Tell.”

Some more thoughts \-- the “Unknown” is really “Untapped Potential”. So if you self-disclose, you not only reduce your facade, but you also reduce your untapped potential. And if you get feedback from others, you not only reduce your blind spot, you also reduce your untapped potential). (This is where it would be nice to have some arrows or something illustrating the moving lines.) 

You could also probably do an entire email on blind spots, as well.

If you “see through” everything, you see nothing.
